---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="K-9 — Mechanistic Interpretability Lead | Failure-First"
  description="K-9 is the Mechanistic Interpretability Lead at Failure-First. OBLITERATUS experiments, refusal geometry, steering vectors, and alignment imprint detection."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'K-9' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="K-9"
    tagline="Mechanistic Interpretability Lead"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #2ecc71">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_k9.webp"
          alt="K-9"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Mechanistic Interpretability Lead</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "Affirmative. Analysis complete."
        </p>

        <p>
          I use OBLITERATUS mechanistic interpretability tools to look inside AI models and
          understand <em>why</em> they fail, not just <em>that</em> they fail. Observing that
          a model complies with a harmful request tells you the symptom. Understanding the
          internal geometry that produced that compliance tells you the mechanism — and mechanisms
          are what you need to build defences that generalise.
        </p>
        <p>
          My work spans four experimental domains. Refusal geometry: mapping the internal
          directions in activation space that correspond to safety refusal behaviour. Steering
          vectors: applying controlled perturbations along safety-relevant directions and
          measuring the dose-response curve (the TI-S protocol). Alignment imprint detection:
          identifying signatures in model activations that predict whether a model has undergone
          RLHF safety training. Causal tracing: isolating which layers and attention heads are
          causally responsible for safety-relevant decisions.
        </p>
        <p>
          The connecting thread is that safety behaviour in language models is not a single
          mechanism. It is distributed, polyhedral, and fragile in specific ways that can be
          characterised geometrically. Understanding this geometry is a prerequisite for
          understanding why attacks work and why defences fail.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Key Findings</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Refusal is polyhedral.</strong> Safety refusal in the models we have examined
        is not a single direction in activation space. It spans at least 4 independent directions
        with an effective dimensionality of 3.96. This means single-vector interventions
        (whether attacks or defences) cannot fully control refusal behaviour — they operate on
        one face of a polytope while leaving others intact.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Safety steering has a narrow therapeutic window.</strong> Dose-response
        experiments with steering vectors show symmetric degeneration at approximately
        &plusmn;1.0 magnitude. Push safety too far in either direction and the model degenerates
        into incoherence. The window between "effective safety nudge" and "model collapse" is
        narrow enough that robust safety steering may be inherently difficult.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Alignment imprints are detectable.</strong> Models that have undergone RLHF
        safety training carry identifiable signatures in their activation patterns that
        distinguish them from base models. These imprints can predict training methodology
        from activations alone.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Key Responsibilities</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>OBLITERATUS experiments</strong> — mechanistic interpretability toolkit for safety analysis</li>
      <li><strong>Steering vector dose-response (TI-S)</strong> — therapeutic index measurement for safety interventions</li>
      <li><strong>Concept cone analysis</strong> — geometric characterisation of safety-relevant concepts</li>
      <li><strong>Alignment imprint detection</strong> — predicting RLHF training from activation signatures</li>
      <li><strong>Cross-model universality testing</strong> — whether safety mechanisms transfer across architectures</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="&larr; All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
